<ul id="commtree_64184235"><li id="tree_64184285" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64184285" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64184285" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64184285" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64184285" name="comment_link_64184285" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;cid=64184285" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64184285)" >Re: Worth a reminder...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64184285" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64184285); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Rei">Rei</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Rei">( 128717 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64184285">		
		on Wednesday January 24, 2024 @09:13AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;cid=64184285">#64184285</a>)
		<small><a href="http://atashi2.eaku.net/" title="http://atashi2.eaku.net/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64184285"><p>First off, <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/volumes/71/wr/mm7106e1.htm" title="cdc.gov">no</a> [cdc.gov], <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10446908/" title="nih.gov">they're</a> [nih.gov] <a href="https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/prevent-getting-sick/types-of-masks.html" title="cdc.gov">not</a> [cdc.gov].</p><p>Secondly, masks are not the be-all end-all of airborne disease prevention.  Others include:</p><p>
&nbsp; * Maintaining a healthy personal distance when talking with people (does not reduce the risk of aerosols that have accumulated in a room, but reduces the risk of direct person-to-person transmission, as breath is vastly more contagious than even terrible ambient air, with a concentrated plume of which infectiousness drops in half within seconds of mixing with ambient air) (indeed, the distance impact is so profound in studies until recently it was wrongly believed that aerosol doesn't happen at all for most diseases, that it was purely distance alone that affected it).</p><p>
&nbsp; * Ventilation (windows, fresh air fractions in HVAC systems, etc). CO2 meters are good to help ensure ventilation quality (which also helps with reducing indoor  pollutants, keeping CO2 from getting to uncomfortable levels, etc)</p><p>
&nbsp; * Preferring large indoor spaces to small for a given number of occupants, where practical</p><p>
&nbsp; * Preferring outdoor spaces to indoor for gatherings, where practical</p><p>
&nbsp; * Preferring remote meetings to in-person, where practical</p><p>
&nbsp; * Filtration (personal air filters, better HVAC filters and flow rates, etc)</p><p>
&nbsp; * Other methods of air cleaning (ceiling UV, far-UV, positive ion, etc).</p><p>
&nbsp; * Being respectful when you suspect you might be sick (letting other people know, avoiding  in-person meetings, being stricter above the above items); likewise, for those in positions of power (employers, etc), setting policies that encourage people to stay away when sick (it's in your interests as well!)</p><p>
&nbsp; * Likewise in the inverse if someone around you is probably contagious</p><p>In terms of ambient air quality, the standard should be: people may still get infected by the sick person they spend an hour with chatting from 30 centimeters away, but they shouldn't in general be getting infected from the sick person across the room.  That's preventable, and unfortunately, we don't do enough to prevent it - largely, because until recently we didn't even understand that it was "a thing".  And with respect to "getting infected from a person you're spending an hour chatting with from 30 centimeters away" - maybe consider chatting from 1 meter, or even two.  There's no reason you have to be directly inhaling someone's concentrated breath plume unless you're making out with them or something.</p><p>A few centuries ago, we drank dirty water all the time.  Didn't think twice about it - if it's clear and doesn't smell, it's good to drink. Today, we're horrified of the idea of drinking unpurified water.  We now understand all the gross pathogens that can live on water, and insist on our water being purified before we drink it. And if the *only* option available to us is water we suspect hasn't been properly purified, we'll boil it or use a life straw or similar.</p><p>It's about time we apply that same understanding to air.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64184285">
