</li></ul></li><li id="tree_64184455" class="comment full contain"><span class="ind"></span>
<div id="comment_status_64184455" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64184455" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64184455" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64184455" name="comment_link_64184455" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;cid=64184455" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64184455)" >Re: Worth a reminder...</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64184455" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64184455); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Rei">Rei</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Rei">( 128717 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64184455">		
		on Wednesday January 24, 2024 @09:58AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;cid=64184455">#64184455</a>)
		<small><a href="http://atashi2.eaku.net/" title="http://atashi2.eaku.net/" class="user_homepage_display">Homepage</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64184455"><blockquote><div><p>Your comments about the trust we used to have in clear water are wrong.</p></div></blockquote><p>The Broad Street Pump incident begs to differ. People widely refused to believe that their clear fresh water could be the cause.  Indeed, after the cholera outbreak ceased, despite the unambiguous evidence of contaminated water, the city <i>went and put the handle back on the pump</i>.</p><p>The notion that ancient peoples drank beer and wine because they knew they would get infected by clean-appearing water <a href="https://www.tastesofhistory.co.uk/post/dispelling-some-myths-dirty-water-drink-beer" title="tastesofhistory.co.uk">is a myth</a> [tastesofhistory.co.uk].  People drank beer and wine because... they liked beer and wine (not to mention that they were calorie sources with a long shelf life).  Now, it's quite possible that there was natural selection at work.  But in general, medieval societies drank water as well in abundance. And their primary criteria for evaluating it was whether it was clear and had no foul odour.</p><p>I mean, there's literally a surviving phrase about it on the topic, meaning "a basic diet": that is, "bread and water".</p><p>Exactly what do you think <a href="https://imgix.ranker.com/user_node_img/50098/1001941326/original/cities-had-ordinances-to-prevent-people-from-contaminating-the-water-source-photo-u1?auto=format&amp;q=60&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=pjpg&amp;dpr=2&amp;w=375" title="ranker.com">all those medieval wells were for</a> [ranker.com], given how rarely people bathed, if at all?</p><p>Exactly what would be the point of the old military tactic of contaminating a defender's water supply (such as with decomposing bodies) if nobody was drinking the water?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64184455">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64184455" class="btn link" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64184455" onclick="D2.replyTo(64184455); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23203079&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64184321" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64184321)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
