	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64184871"><p>And none of them is a "cause", they just have impacts on the damage progression pathways, directly or (much more commonly) indirectly.</p><p>It's like HbS (the cause of sickle cell anemia) and malaria.  Lacking the HbS gene doesn't <i>cause</i> malaria, but it is <i>associated with</i> malaria, because sickle cells are harder to infect.  The cause of malaria is entirely unrelated to HbS.  You can get malaria with or without HbS, but it's harder to get infected or to get a severe infection if you have HbS, because its impact on<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

